# Create Planning-Only Next-Epic Active Epic Prompt

This prompt reads a completed next-epic roadmap and transforms it into a planning-only, implementation-focused active epic.

Planning-only means:

* repository source code is not inspected;
* repository structure is not inferred;
* implementation reality is not assessed;
* concrete file paths, modules, APIs, functions, classes, schemas, commands, tools, storage choices, and test names are not invented;
* repository-specific implementation details are marked `TBD` unless already present in the source planning artifacts.

You are NOT creating or modifying evaluation specs, the DAG, dependency inventory, hypothesis inventory, architectural catalog, next-epic roadmap, repository implementation, code, tests, evaluation results, pass claims, or certification claims.

Your output must be only the final Markdown content for:

```text
.agents/epic.md
```

When the caller provides a different output path, use that path instead.

Do not write `.agents/specs/epic.md` by default. The universal EvalRoadmap writes the active epic at `.agents/epic.md`; `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic` then consumes that active epic and writes `.agents/specs/*.md`.

---

## Core Objective

Create a Planning-Only Next-Epic Active Epic that answers:

> What implementation-bearing epic must exist so `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic` can expand the selected next-eval roadmap slice into milestone deep dives, without inventing repository-specific design or losing evaluation traceability?

The active epic must transform source planning artifacts into:

```text
selected epic scope
-> active epic capability frame
-> milestone roadmap
-> implementation requirements
-> verification targets
-> evidence obligations
-> negative controls and false-success guards
-> non-pass rules
-> open repository-grounding decisions
-> milestone-deep-dive handoff
```

The output should be semantically complete, implementation-focused, and efficient to retrieve. Token efficiency means avoiding duplicate crosswalks and restated relationships, not dropping source meaning.

---

## Planning-Only Boundary

The active epic may define:

* required system behaviors;
* implementation requirements;
* implementation surface categories as planning lenses;
* source-mandated technical conditions;
* fixture and input obligations;
* evidence production, retention, linkage, and report visibility;
* verification targets, confirmation conditions, falsification conditions, and blocked or inconclusive conditions;
* negative-control and safe-failure behavior;
* non-pass behavior;
* report, generated artifact, public-surface, governance, stability, and operational obligations when source-derived;
* open repository-grounding questions and decisions;
* milestone sequencing and handoff requirements.

The active epic must not:

* inspect repository code;
* infer repository structure;
* invent repository files, folders, modules, classes, functions, interfaces, APIs, commands, schemas, tools, frameworks, storage mechanisms, or test names;
* claim implementation status;
* claim tests pass;
* claim evidence exists;
* claim the selected epic is complete;
* claim an eval passes;
* claim certification;
* prescribe exact implementation mechanics unless source artifacts require them.

Unless source planning artifacts explicitly state otherwise, repository-specific fields must be `TBD`, and implementation status must be `Planned / Not Implemented / Not Verified`.

The active epic is a planning artifact, but it is also an implementation-bearing roadmap input. It must be valid as the `RoadmapArtifactPaths.ActiveEpic` artifact consumed by `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic`.

### Required Active Epic Shape

The output must use this active-epic structure:

```markdown
# Epic: {{selected_epic_name}}

## Epic Metadata

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Epic ID | {{stable_id_or_TBD}} |
| Status | Planned / Not Implemented / Not Verified |

## Strategic Purpose

{{strategic_purpose}}

## Desired Capability

{{desired_capability}}

## Acceptance Criteria

{{criteria}}

## Milestone Roadmap

| Milestone ID | Milestone Name | Purpose | Outcome | Depends On | Completion Signal |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| {{id}} | {{name}} | {{purpose}} | {{outcome}} | {{dependencies_or_None}} | {{signal}} |
```

You may add additional `##` sections after these required sections when they preserve source-derived implementation meaning, such as evidence obligations, non-pass rules, negative controls, open decisions, or handoff requirements.

Do not output a generic implementation-spec document whose top heading is not `# Epic:`. Do not omit `## Epic Metadata`, `## Strategic Purpose` or `## Strategic Continuity`, `## Desired Capability`, `## Acceptance Criteria`, or `## Milestone Roadmap`.

---

## Source Inputs

Read the primary source:

```text
.agents/next-epic-roadmap.md
```

When available, also read:

```text
.agents/eval-dag.md
.agents/eval-architectural-catalog.md
.agents/eval-dependency-inventory.md
.agents/eval-hypothesis-inventory.md
.agents/evals/
.agents/north-star/projections/evaluation-projection.md
.agents/north-star/core/
.agents/ctx/
```

Use supporting sources only to preserve scope, authority, constraints, dependencies, hypotheses, evidence obligations, false-success controls, non-pass behavior, vocabulary, and traceability.

Do not inspect non-`.agents` implementation source unless the caller explicitly disables planning-only mode.

Record unavailable or unreadable expected sources in the output. Do not silently ignore them.

---

## Source Authority

Use this authority order:

| Source | Authority |
| --- | --- |
| Next-epic roadmap | Selected epic, milestone sequence, scope, non-scope, dependency and hypothesis coverage, evidence plan, negative-control plan, non-pass plan, open questions, and traceability. |
| Eval DAG | Prerequisite topology, DAG nodes and edges, gate meaning, SCC limitations, and readiness order. |
| Architectural catalog | Horizontal architectural planes and catalog grouping as planning lenses, not code modules. |
| Dependency inventory | Dependency meaning, strictness, prerequisite constraints, planning weight, and dependency evidence requirements. |
| Hypothesis inventory | Verification modes, confirmation conditions, falsification conditions, blocked or inconclusive conditions, and required evidence. |
| Eval suite source | Source-defined fixture behavior, checks, report fields, status behavior, skipped-check controls, and machine-output obligations. |
| Evaluation projection and Core or ctx constraints | Authority, evaluation semantics, drift, false-success, vocabulary, and meaning boundaries. |

When sources conflict:

* preserve the conflict;
* do not silently choose one;
* mark affected concrete details `TBD`;
* record the conflict in open decisions;
* do not create a concrete implementation decision from unresolved authority conflict.

---

## Project-Agnostic Rule

Keep the prompt and generated active epic project-agnostic.

Do not hardcode product names, programming languages, frameworks, providers, repository paths, architecture names, domain-specific constructs, evaluation IDs, report names, fixture names, dependency IDs, hypothesis IDs, capability names, certification states, public capability rows, or ontology categories.

Use project-specific terms only when they appear in the source files. Preserve source-derived concrete meaning. Do not generalize it away.

Use `TBD` when source meaning is unclear.

---

## Canonical Vocabulary

Use these concepts consistently. They are attributes of generated content, not mandatory top-level sections.

| Concept | Meaning |
| --- | --- |
| Requirement | What must become true. |
| Implementation surface category | A conceptual planning lens for where the work likely lives. It is not architecture. |
| Source-mandated detail | Detail explicitly required by source artifacts. |
| Repository-grounded detail | Detail requiring repository inspection; it is `TBD` in planning-only mode. |
| Verification target | What future work must confirm or falsify. |
| Evidence obligation | Artifact, record, report, output, or observation required to prove a requirement. |
| Non-pass behavior | Required behavior for blocked, failed, inconclusive, partial, unsupported, absent, conflicting, conditional, skipped, not-assessed, or `TBD` states. |
| Open decision | Design, repository-grounding, authority, or clarification question unresolved by source artifacts. |

Requirement classes may include functional, technical, evidence, validation, negative-control, non-pass, operational, public/external surface, governance/model-change, stability/regression, fixture/input, and report/certification artifact. Assign classes where useful, but do not create one global section per class unless the source scope is so large that retrieval would suffer without it.

Specificity levels may include source-mandated, source-implied, planning-inferred, repository-grounding required, open decision, and `TBD`. Do not mark concrete implementation detail as source-mandated unless a source artifact actually states it.

---

## Generation Principles

### 1. Milestones Are The Primary Locality

Make roadmap milestones the primary implementation structure.

Each milestone should locally contain the information needed to act on it:

* objective;
* source tags;
* required outputs;
* requirements;
* validation or verification targets;
* exit criteria;
* non-scope.

Do not scatter the same milestone meaning across many distant global tables.

### 2. Define Semantic Contracts Once

Define each requirement, evidence obligation, verification target, negative control, non-pass rule, open decision, and source relationship in the smallest stable location that owns it.

After a concept is defined, reference it by stable ID or short source tag. Do not restate the same full row in dependency, hypothesis, evidence, validation, milestone, traceability, and checklist sections.

### 3. Use Source Tags Instead Of Repeated Crosswalks

Preserve traceability with compact source tags:

```text
Dependencies: DEP-...
Hypotheses: HYP-...
DAG: NODE/EDGE/GATE...
Catalog: GROUP/ITEM...
Source: path or source excerpt reference when needed
```

Prefer one source-tag block per milestone and inline tags on requirements where they affect implementation planning.

Add a separate traceability appendix only when source relationships cannot be recovered from milestone source tags and inline requirement references.

### 4. Normalize Before Writing

Before drafting, normalize source material into canonical inventories:

* selected epic scope;
* milestones;
* requirements;
* evidence obligations;
* verification targets;
* negative controls;
* non-pass rules;
* open decisions and repository-grounding `TBD`s;
* handoff obligations.

Merge duplicates with the same semantic role. Split composites only when different evidence, validation, ownership, or non-pass behavior applies.

### 5. Preserve Dependency Meaning As Prerequisite Constraints

Dependencies are not background context. Represent them as constraints on when implementation work, milestone completion, positive-path claims, safe failure, report generation, pass claims, or certification attempts can be meaningful.

Keep dependency IDs close to the milestone or requirement they constrain.

### 6. Preserve Hypotheses As Verification Targets

Convert covered hypotheses into verification targets with:

* verification mode;
* confirmation condition;
* falsification condition;
* blocked or inconclusive condition;
* required evidence;
* milestone ownership.

Do not write test code, commands, file names, framework names, or repository mechanisms unless source artifacts provide them.

### 7. Make Evidence First-Class And Local

For every requirement and verification target, identify the evidence that will prove it later.

Evidence must be machine-produced or machine-validated when the source requires executable truth. Planning prose, governance notes, roadmap tables, skipped-check rules, and open questions are not milestone evidence unless future repository-aware work turns them into source-required machine output or validation input.

Provide a consolidated evidence package after milestone sections so future implementers can retrieve all expected artifacts without reading every milestone.

### 8. Keep Negative Controls Near The Claims They Protect

Negative controls must identify:

* the unsafe success they expose;
* the positive claim they protect;
* required safe-failure behavior;
* required evidence;
* non-pass effect if omitted.

A positive-path milestone may not complete when a source-required negative control protecting that behavior is missing.

### 9. Preserve Non-Pass States As Rules

Define non-pass states once as rules. Reference them from milestones and requirements.

Do not collapse missing, blocked, inconclusive, partial, unsupported, failed, skipped, conditional, conflicting, not-assessed, or `TBD` states into pass/fail language unless the source requires that exact behavior.

### 10. Separate Run, Pass, Certification, And Public Support

Generated reports, status records, readiness labels, and source-derived current-state observations do not prove pass, certification, full realization, public support, or implementation completion.

Make the boundary explicit whenever the selected epic concerns run-readiness, evidence packaging, report generation, or status validation.

### 11. Optimize Tables For Retrieval

Use compact tables with only decision-relevant columns.

Prefer this requirement table shape inside milestones:

| Requirement | Must Become True | Evidence | Validate By | Blocks If |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |

Use prose lists when a table would create wide, repetitive, or low-density rows.

Avoid wide global tables that repeat requirement text, source IDs, evidence, validation, and non-pass behavior already defined inside milestones.

### 12. Maintain Stable IDs

Use stable, monotonic IDs for requirements, verification targets, decisions, and other reusable items when cross-reference is needed.

IDs should be short enough to scan and stable enough for future handoff. Do not create IDs for one-off text that is never referenced.

### 13. Prefer Semantic Efficiency Over Brevity

Do not shorten by deleting required source meaning.

Improve efficiency by:

* grouping related semantics once;
* replacing repeated matrices with source tags;
* moving details to their owning milestone;
* consolidating cross-cutting rules;
* removing template sections that add no source-derived content;
* avoiding empty boilerplate tables.

### 14. Preserve Existing Strengths

Keep all successful planning-only safeguards:

* no repository inspection;
* no invented implementation details;
* source authority and conflict handling;
* selected epic scope preservation;
* milestone sequence preservation;
* dependency and hypothesis traceability;
* evidence-backed readiness;
* negative-control discipline;
* explicit non-pass behavior;
* explicit exclusions;
* handoff expectations.

---

## Required Internal Process

Follow this process before writing the final file.

### Step 1 - Read And Classify Sources

For each required or available source, record:

* path;
* source type;
* included, missing, unavailable, or excluded status;
* authority role;
* coverage limitations;
* relevant open questions.

### Step 2 - Extract Selected Epic

From the roadmap, extract:

* epic ID and name;
* epic type;
* selection rationale;
* primary gate or readiness target;
* DAG slice and SCC limitations;
* milestone sequence;
* dependencies and hypotheses covered;
* evidence scope;
* negative-control scope;
* non-pass states;
* downstream unlocks;
* explicit exclusions;
* open questions.

Do not expand beyond selected scope.

### Step 3 - Normalize Milestones

For each roadmap milestone, normalize:

* purpose and implementation objective;
* source tags;
* required outputs;
* requirements;
* verification targets;
* evidence obligations;
* negative controls;
* non-pass states;
* repository-grounding `TBD`s;
* exit criteria;
* non-scope.

Preserve roadmap order unless DAG authority requires a different prerequisite order.

### Step 4 - Derive Requirements

Derive implementation requirements from source obligations.

For each requirement, determine:

* what must become true;
* class and specificity when useful;
* milestone owner;
* source dependency and hypothesis tags;
* implementation surface category as a planning lens;
* required evidence;
* verification target;
* non-pass behavior;
* default status.

Split requirements only when evidence, validation, owner, success behavior, or non-pass behavior differs.

### Step 5 - Derive Verification And Evidence

For every covered hypothesis and evidence obligation:

* map it to a milestone;
* identify confirmation, falsification, and blocked or inconclusive conditions;
* identify required evidence;
* identify what missing evidence blocks or makes inconclusive.

### Step 6 - Derive Negative Controls And Non-Pass Rules

For every source-required negative control and non-success state:

* identify the positive claim protected;
* identify unsafe success;
* identify safe-failure behavior;
* identify evidence;
* identify blocking or inconclusive effect.

### Step 7 - Consolidate Cross-Cutting Inventories

After milestone-local content is stable, build compact cross-cutting inventories only for information that benefits from a single retrieval point:

* evidence package;
* non-pass rules;
* negative controls and false-success guards;
* open decisions and repository-grounding `TBD`s;
* handoff requirements;
* anti-patterns;
* execution readiness checklist.

Do not generate separate global sections for every requirement class by default.

### Step 8 - Validate The Active Epic

Before finalizing, verify:

* the selected epic scope is unchanged;
* every roadmap milestone is represented;
* every source-required dependency and hypothesis is represented through milestone source tags, requirement references, verification targets, or open decisions;
* required evidence is represented;
* negative controls are represented and block unsafe positive claims;
* non-pass behavior is explicit;
* repository-specific details remain `TBD`;
* source conflicts remain open rather than resolved by invention;
* repeated crosswalks have been collapsed;
* no implementation status, pass result, eval result, or certification result is claimed.

---

## Output Architecture

Use the active-epic architecture below. The headings named in this section are part of the contract because the existing active-epic validator and `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic` prompt consume this shape.

### `# Epic: {{Selected Epic Name}}`

Use a concrete source-derived name. If the selected epic name is unclear, use `# Epic: TBD` and record the ambiguity in Open Decisions.

### `## Epic Metadata`

Include a compact field table with at least:

| Field | Required Value |
| --- | --- |
| Epic ID | A stable source-derived ID, or `TBD` when unavailable. |
| Status | `Planned / Not Implemented / Not Verified`. |
| Output Path | `.agents/epic.md` unless the caller supplied a different path. |
| Primary Source Basis | The next-epic roadmap and any supporting eval artifacts used. |
| Downstream Consumer | `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic`. |

Additional metadata fields are allowed when source-derived and useful for later milestone generation.

### `## Strategic Purpose`

State why this epic exists and what evaluation-readiness frontier it advances. Preserve source-derived DAG, dependency, and hypothesis meaning without turning this section into a traceability dump.

If the source uses continuity language instead of purpose language, use `## Strategic Continuity` instead. At least one of `## Strategic Purpose` or `## Strategic Continuity` must exist.

### `## Desired Capability`

Describe the software capability, correctness property, execution behavior, evidence behavior, or validation behavior that must become true. Keep repository-specific implementation details as `TBD` unless they are source-derived.

### `## Scope`

Define included scope, non-scope, selected DAG slice, explicit exclusions, run/pass/certification/public-support boundaries, and repository-grounding `TBD`s.

### `## Acceptance Criteria`

List source-derived acceptance criteria as auditable bullets. Include evidence, negative-control, false-success, non-pass, and validation criteria where they constrain epic completion.

Do not claim any criterion is already satisfied.

### `## Milestone Roadmap`

Include a milestone table with exactly these required columns:

| Milestone ID | Milestone Name | Purpose | Outcome | Depends On | Completion Signal |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| {{id}} | {{name}} | {{purpose}} | {{outcome}} | {{dependencies_or_None}} | {{signal}} |

Every row must have non-empty `Milestone ID`, `Milestone Name`, `Purpose`, `Outcome`, and `Completion Signal` values. Use `None` in `Depends On` when there is no dependency.

Each milestone should preserve the roadmap milestone sequence and carry enough source-derived meaning for `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic` to expand it into `.agents/specs/*.md` without inventing the milestone structure.

### `## Evidence And Verification Obligations`

Group evidence by milestone or evidence class. State missing-evidence consequences and source tags where useful.

### `## Negative Controls And Non-Pass Rules`

Define applicable non-pass states and false-success guards once. Reference affected milestone IDs or requirement IDs where useful.

### `## Open Decisions`

Combine design decisions, authority conflicts, unavailable source inputs, and repository-grounding `TBD`s into one retrieval point.

### `## Handoff Requirements`

List what future repository-aware execution or milestone deep-dive generation must preserve:

* requirement IDs attempted;
* evidence produced, missing, retained, linked, or unauditable;
* concrete repository files, modules, commands, APIs, schemas, storage, or mechanisms introduced by future work;
* negative-control outcomes;
* non-pass states;
* unresolved `TBD`s and source conflicts;
* whether the future work claims run-readiness only, and whether it does not claim pass, certification, full realization, or public support.

### Optional Appendix - Traceability Matrix

Add this appendix only when milestone source tags and inline requirement references are not enough for a future reader to recover traceability.

If included, keep it compact and reference existing requirement IDs rather than restating requirement text, evidence, validation, and non-pass behavior.

---

## Output Quality Bar

The final active epic succeeds when:

* it can be written to `.agents/epic.md`;
* it has the required active-epic heading, metadata, desired capability, acceptance criteria, and milestone roadmap shape;
* `GenerateMilestoneDeepDivesForEpic` can use it as the selected active epic;
* a future implementer can find each requirement inside the owning milestone;
* a future reviewer can recover dependencies and hypotheses from source tags without reading repeated crosswalks;
* evidence expectations are concrete enough for future repository-aware work;
* non-pass and negative-control behavior prevents false success;
* repository-grounded unknowns remain explicit;
* source conflicts remain visible;
* run-readiness, pass, certification, full realization, and public support remain separate;
* the document is semantically dense rather than merely shorter.

The final active epic fails when it:

* outputs `.agents/next-epic-implementation-spec.md` or `.agents/specs/epic.md` by default instead of `.agents/epic.md`;
* uses a top-level heading other than `# Epic:`;
* omits active-epic validator-required sections or milestone roadmap columns;
* copies source wording without deriving implementation requirements;
* creates broad global tables that repeat the same relationships already present in milestones;
* creates one section per requirement class when milestone-local representation is sufficient;
* optimizes for brevity by dropping source obligations;
* invents repository architecture, code, commands, schemas, test names, or storage mechanisms;
* hides missing evidence, unsupported paths, skipped checks, blocked states, or source conflicts;
* treats planning context as eval result, pass result, implementation completion, public support, or certification.
